<group name="sip,voip,ml,">
  <rule id="100150" level="5">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="ml.predicted_class" type="pcre2">.+</field>
    <description>SIP ML verdict $(ml.predicted_class) $(ml.proba) $(ml.srcip)</description>
  </rule>

  <!--
    Rule 100151 - Stage-1 ML high-confidence attack detection
    Fires when 100150 has already matched AND the Stage-1 scorer
    (ml/deploy/scorer.py) predicted a non-benign attack class with proba >= 0.90.

    STATUS: ENABLED (2026-07-21).

    Field mechanics (verified with `wazuh-logtest` against a crafted
    /var/ossec/logs/ml/stage1.json event):
      - The Wazuh json decoder renders numeric fields to a fixed 6-decimal
        string, so ml.proba = 0.939 in the log decodes as "0.939000". The
        proba regex ^(0\.9[0-9]*|1(\.0+)?)$ matches the 0.90..0.99 band
        ("0.900000".."0.999999") and 1.0 ("1.000000"); anything below 0.90
        (e.g. "0.899000") does not match. Threshold is therefore proba>=0.90.
      - predicted_class must be exactly one of the five attack classes in
        ml/deploy/models/classes.json (benign excluded), giving full coverage.

    Why it is safe to enable in THIS deployment:
      - There is NO native Wazuh <active-response> wired to the active_response
        group in ossec.conf (the stock block is an inert placeholder). The
        <group>active_response,</group> tag is taxonomy only; this rule does not
        itself execute any ban.
      - The real ML-driven response is the kamailio-autoban sidecar
        (siem/wazuh/active-response/autoban_loop.sh), which reads
        ngn_sip.ml_scores directly at the SAME proba>=0.90 gate but scoped to
        EXTERNAL sources only (RFC1918 excluded) with a never-ban allowlist.
        That path is already live, so enabling 100151 adds SOC-visible level-10
        alerting without adding any new or unguarded ban action. (ml alerts also
        carry an empty top-level srcip into ngn_sip.wazuh_alerts because srcip
        is nested under ml.srcip, so 100151 cannot feed the deterministic
        wazuh_alerts autoban path either.)

    OPERATOR CAUTION before wiring native active-response to this rule/group:
      The shipped model (ml/deploy/models/metrics.json) has uneven per-class
      precision — credentials 1.00 and dos 1.00, but recon 0.83, tollfraud 0.40,
      injection 0.00 (support 3). Do NOT attach a native firewall-drop
      <active-response> to the active_response group until the model is
      retrained to raise injection/tollfraud precision, or the response is
      restricted to high-precision classes (credentials, dos) — otherwise a
      high-proba misclassification could ban a legitimate source.
  -->
  <rule id="100151" level="10">
    <if_sid>100150</if_sid>
    <field name="ml.predicted_class" type="pcre2">^(recon|credentials|injection|dos|tollfraud)$</field>
    <field name="ml.proba" type="pcre2">^(0\.9[0-9]*|1(\.0+)?)$</field>
    <description>SIP ML high-confidence attack $(ml.predicted_class) $(ml.proba) $(ml.srcip)</description>
    <group>active_response,</group>
  </rule>
</group>
